Assignment 01 – A Conversation Between Brain and AI
Course: ITAI 4374 – Neuroscience as a Model for AI
Student: Orhan Gumus
Semester: Spring 2026

The Problem I Was Trying to Solve
The goal of this assignment was to creatively explore the similarities and differences between biological intelligence and artificial intelligence by writing a structured dialogue between a human brain and an AI system. The challenge was to ground the conversation in real neuroscience and AI concepts while making it accessible and engaging.

My Approach
I structured the dialogue around four key comparison points identified in course readings: learning mechanisms, energy efficiency, memory and decision-making, and the value of collaboration. Each exchange in the dialogue introduced a real concept:

Hebbian learning ("cells that fire together, wire together") — the biological basis for synaptic strengthening and the inspiration for neural network weight updates
Energy efficiency — the human brain operates on roughly 20 watts, far less than large AI models requiring data centers
Generalization — the brain learns quickly from limited examples, while AI typically requires massive datasets
David Marr's three levels of analysis — computational, algorithmic, and implementational — as a shared framework for understanding both systems


Results and What They Mean
The dialogue format made abstract neuroscience and AI concepts concrete and relatable. The key insight that emerged was that the brain and AI are not competitors but complementary systems. The brain excels at intuition, creativity, energy efficiency, and contextual understanding; AI excels at speed, precision, consistency, and large-scale data processing.
This framing — collaboration over competition — became a theme I carried through the rest of the course. It reflects the broader goal of the field: not to replace human intelligence, but to build systems that work alongside it.

